Ticket ID: SEC-DEV-2025-10-LAPTOPI-PLATFORM
Title: Laptop I — Platform Management Software Recovery, Dependency Repair & Thermal Management Restoration
Classification: Endpoint Software Remediation / Platform Stability / Performance & Thermal Management
Status: Resolved – Stable Configuration
Priority: High
Affected Asset: Laptop I (High-Performance Laptop Workstation)
Related Tickets: SYS-VAL-2026-02-LAPTOPI, SEC-DEV-2025-10-LAPTOPI-CLEANOS

Executive Summary
After a Windows 11 feature update and routine driver maintenance, the platform management software became unstable, causing partial loss of thermal, performance, and telemetry management.
Root causes included:
	• Windows servicing stack changes
	• Driver dependency mismatches
	• Residual legacy software components
	• GPU driver telemetry conflicts
	• Missing or outdated Microsoft runtime dependencies (.NET Framework & Visual C++)
Resolution involved full removal of legacy platform management components, driver cleanup using DDU, OS component repair, runtime dependency restoration, and clean installation of the management software.
System now operates with full stability, restored thermal/fan management, and predictable high-performance operation.
Environment
	• Device: Laptop I (High-Performance Laptop Workstation)
	• Operating System: Windows 11 (Latest Version)
	• Platform Management Software: Generic OEM Management Suite
	• GPU Vendor: NVIDIA
	• Location: Romania
	• Usage Profile: Gaming / High-performance workloads / Thermal-sensitive applications
Business Impact
	• Severity: High
	• Impacts:
		○ Loss of fan/thermal profile control
		○ Missing performance/overclocking profile functionality
		○ Reduced temperature telemetry
		○ Risk of thermal throttling and performance instability
	• Operational Risks:
		○ Hardware overheating
		○ Reduced performance stability
		○ System unpredictability under sustained load
Root Cause Analysis
	1. Windows Update Component Changes – Updated system components used by platform management software (WMI, runtime, hardware abstraction).
	2. Legacy Component Residue – Leftover files and registry entries causing driver/service conflicts.
	3. GPU Driver Telemetry Disruption – Required for temperature, performance, and overclocking monitoring; corrupted drivers caused failure.
	4. Runtime Dependency Issues – Outdated or missing Microsoft Visual C++ Redistributables and .NET Framework.
	5. Audio Stack Conflicts – Certain audio enhancement components interfering with software integration.
Remediation Steps
Phase 1 — Management Software Removal & Cleanup
	• Removed software using uninstaller tool
	• Cleared residual folders and registry entries
	• Verified service removal via services.msc
Phase 2 — Version Compatibility Testing
	• Installed previous software version → partial functionality, incompatible
	• Fully removed previous version
Phase 3 — Windows Component Repair
	• Reinstalled Windows Update servicing stack
	• Installed latest .NET Framework updates
Phase 4 — Runtime Dependency Repair
	• Installed / repaired Visual C++ 2015–2022 Redistributables (x64 & x86)
Phase 5 — GPU Driver Cleanup
	• Removed NVIDIA drivers via DDU in Safe Mode
	• Installed OEM-validated GPU drivers via NVCleanstall
Phase 6 — Conflicting Audio Component Removal
	• Removed all third-party audio enhancement software and services
Phase 7 — Clean Management Software Installation
	• Installed management suite primary & supporting packages in correct sequence
	• Verified all services running (e.g., software service, client management service, monitoring service)
Validation & Testing
	• Management software launch successful, no crashes
	• Thermal management fully functional (fan curves, temperature monitoring)
	• Performance profiles and overclocking restored
	• Application and gaming validation: stable FPS, stable thermals, no throttling
	• Startup validation: software auto-load verified
Final System State
	• Status: Fully operational
	• Restored Functionality: Fan control, thermal profiles, performance/overclocking, telemetry, performance modes, audio integration
	• Performance Improvements: Improved thermal stability, FPS consistency, system predictability
Preventive Recommendations
	• Use only latest version of platform management software
	• Install drivers only from verified OEM sources
	• Maintain runtime dependencies (.NET Framework, Visual C++)
	• Avoid conflicting third-party audio software
	• Create restore points before major OS, driver, or platform software updates
Conclusion
Platform management software instability was resolved by addressing legacy software residue, runtime dependencies, GPU driver telemetry, and Windows servicing stack inconsistencies. Laptop I now operates under a stable, fully functional platform management environment with restored thermal and performance control.
